HEADWORD: Hamadryad
<hw>Ham"a*dry`ad</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m"⟦adot⟧*dr⟦imac⟧`⟦acr⟧d)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Hamadryads</plw>
<pr>(-⟦acr⟧dz)</pr>, L. <plw>Hamadryades</plw>
<pr>(-dr⟦imac⟧"⟦adot⟧*d⟦emac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>Hamadryas</ets>, <ets>-adis</ets>, Gr. <grk>"Amadrya`s</grk>;
<grk>"a`ma</grk> together + <grk>dry^s</grk> oak, tree: cf. F.
<ets>hamadryade</ets>. See <er>Same</er>, and <er>Tree</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>A tree nymph whose life
ended with that of the particular tree, usually an oak, which had been
her abode.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large venomous East Indian
snake (<spn>Ophiophagus bungarus</spn>), allied to the cobras.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamadryas</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
